\subtree{
  \title{5. Workmanship & handling standards}

  \ul{
    \li{Hand-solder acceptance to IPC-A-610 Class 2; ESD handling per ANSI/ESD S20.20.}
    \li{bci.place can provide a working station at MOX, 1618 Mission Street, San Francisco, with a fan, air filter, soldering bench, and ESD wrist straps. The assembler may use their own qualified station instead.}
    \li{First power-on behind a current limit; isolated/protected USB for test (per BuildGuide); laser and RF stay OFF until the relevant work item.}
    \li{Eye safety for the 520 nm laser and RF-exposure care are gating, not optional.}
    \li{Diamond prism: UV-cure in a ventilated area; the ~750 µm diamond is a single bulk-sourced grain — handle/track as a high-value small part.}
    \li{Defective/damaged CFM: stop, photograph, report per §9 non-conformance; do not rework factory SMT population without written go-ahead.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{6. Work items}

  \p{Each work item carries assembly tasks and acceptance evidence. Acceptance artifacts are deliverables feeding the WI-11 evidence bundle. Quote each WI as a line in §8.}
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-1 — Inventory & kitting — qty 1 kit}

  \ul{
    \li{Map kit against BOM + DiamondMount parts; record as-received population (§3). Confirm laser/RF OFF and 5 V untrusted until proven.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: population map + shortfall list, signed; laser/RF off condition documented.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-2 — Power rails — qty 1}

  \ul{
    \li{Fit P1 (USB-C) / 5V_SUPP1; prove protection and U6 LM1117 3.3 V before any downstream load. Check R1/R2 divider (5 V / 2.5 V / 0 V) per BuildGuide.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: 5 V and 3.3 V measured.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-3 — Controller bring-up — qty 1}

  \ul{
    \li{Populate OLED1 header, ESP32/ADF4351 sockets (ADF4351 socket solders on the back), BOOT1/EN1; CP2102N (U8) programs ESP32 (U7); OLED + serial report condition. Flash firmware.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: boot log + OLED alive.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-4 — PLL / microwave source — qty 1}

  \ul{
    \li{X1 10 MHz drives U1 ADF4351; ESP32 writes SPI registers (SPI1); confirm \code{LOCK} LED and output (~2880 MHz per stock firmware modes).}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: PLL lock + frequency as configured.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-5 — RF gain & connectors — qty 1}

  \ul{
    \li{Mount ADF4351 (back) + RF amp board (front); link with a short SMA-SMA cable; fit + verify the SMA connectors — use the existing one if it works (V-1); inspect L1/L2 1.9 nH, L3/L4 470 nH, and R6/R7/R9/R10 50 Ω matching; integrate external 40 dB amp; short test antenna to confirm.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: SMA fit + RF continuity + sane bias.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-6 — Optomechanical assembly: diamond prism + laser — qty 1 — major hand-assembly}

  \ul{
    \li{Diamond prism (jewellery-style epoxy mount): in a 10–20 mm silicone mould, layer clear UV-cured epoxy; form a small loop of 24 AWG enamelled-copper microwave aerial and place it around the ~750 µm NV diamond during layering; seat the BPW34 photodiode directly below and close to the diamond; add the red gel filter; UV-cure. Result: the "diamond holding prism" with aerial + photodiode leads.}
    \li{Laser: mount the 520 nm green laser module; wire to the 5V/GND socket watching polarity.}
    \li{Co-locate laser spot, diamond prism, and microwave aerial in the printed holder.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: cured prism (diamond + aerial loop + BPW34 + gel), laser mounted, visible green-on-diamond alignment.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-7 — Detector path — qty 1}

  \ul{
    \li{Connect the assembled prism's BPW34 leads to the PHOTODIODE1 (1×3) socket; verify the D4 path converts red (~620 nm) fluorescence to current.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: dark/light contrast at the detector.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-8 — Front-end / ADC — qty 1}

  \ul{
    \li{U5 TL082 conditions detector current (add C1/C2 only if using the op-amp as an integrator); ADC_SIGNAL reaches ESP32 and TP1 / TP2 (MUX_OUT).}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: unsaturated baseline.}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-9 — Sweep QA — qty 1}

  \ul{
    \li{ESP32 sweeps 128 points, averages ADC, streams the trace.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: repeatable ODMR dip candidate (baseline + dip + recorded settings).}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-10 — Build the INA333 acquisition-isolation daughterboard — qty 1 — known issue / manual optimization (KI-1)}

  \ul{
    \li{This is new work, not a populate step. The INA333 daughterboard is not on the Uncut Gem PCB as shipped — the assembler fabricates/builds it from scratch (INA333 instrumentation amp + headers/probes, off-BOM).}
    \li{The error being fixed: on the main board, RF energy couples into the detector / \code{ADC_SIGNAL} line, corrupting the analog baseline so ODMR dips are noisy or ambiguous. This is the designer's known defect — the board ships needing it corrected.}
    \li{The fix: route the detector-side input into the INA333 and have it drive one clean, isolated single-ended \code{ADC_SIGNAL} to the ESP32. Map U5 / J6 / TP nodes; isolate the old TL082 output before injecting the clean ADC drive. Reversible — no re-spin of the main PCB.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: lower-noise acquisition with no RF-sweep regression (stock-vs-rework comparison).}
  }
}

\subtree{
  \title{WI-11 — Release QA / evidence bundle — qty 1}

  \ul{
    \li{Compile: board photo, rail measurements, boot log, PLL/LOCK trace, RF continuity, prism + laser alignment photo, detector dark/light, ODMR sweep, INA333 before/after, firmware hash, BOM counts.}
    \li{Acceptance evidence: evidence bundle delivered for bci.place review.}
  }
}

